{"id": "4845", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4845", "title": "Visceratuant", "text": "Visceratuant is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; , a type of &lt;a href=\"Shields\"&gt;shield&lt;/a&gt; from \"\".\nLike most smaller shields, Visceratuant has a slightly lower &lt;a href=\"defense\"&gt;defense&lt;/a&gt; but a higher chance of &lt;a href=\"block\"&gt;block&lt;/a&gt;. This is a &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt;-oriented shield as well with its +1 Sorceress skill level bonus.\nDefensively, this shield is outclassed by things like and &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary%20Rune%20Word\"&gt;Sanctuary Rune Word&lt;/a&gt;, which offer resistances and other powerful defensive properties in addition to high blocking. Offensively, this shield is outclassed by the &lt;a href=\"Spirit%20Rune%20Word\"&gt;Spirit Rune Word&lt;/a&gt; for those who can create it, which offers other caster-oriented bonus like mana and &lt;a href=\"Faster%20Cast%20Rate\"&gt;Faster Cast Rate&lt;/a&gt;.\nIt does offer value as a compromise between two goals, though. For sorceresses who wish to block, but are not too bothered about other defensive properties (primarily resistance), this shield is a good option to squeeze in a little offensive power as well. It also has very low strength requirement, which is a plus (in contrast, the lowest strength requirement Spirit can have is 156 strength). Its very low level requirement makes it an excellent mid-game shield, particularly for Sorceresses, who'd be hard-pressed to find anything better for quite a while.\u00a0\nFor blocking purposes, the player should consider upgrading it, as it bestows another 12% chance to block. It also raises the strength requirement to 77, though.\nStats.\nDefense: 100-125 \nRequired Level: 28\nRequired Strength: 38\nDurability: 68\nChance to Block:\nPaladin &lt;a href=\"Smite\"&gt;Smite&lt;/a&gt; Damage: 8 To 12"}
{"id": "41715", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=41715", "title": "Vischar Orous", "text": "Vischar Orous was the chief librarian of the &lt;a href=\"Zharesh%20Covenant\"&gt;Zharesh Covenant&lt;/a&gt;. He conducted research on the &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evils\"&gt;Prime Evils&lt;/a&gt; and other &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;s, obtained through information gathered from &lt;a href=\"Vizjerei\"&gt;Vizjerei&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Mage\"&gt;Mage&lt;/a&gt;s who summoned demons into &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;.\nOrous's careful and scholarly research endured past his death, and was passed down to future generations through historical and scientific &lt;a href=\"tome\"&gt;tome&lt;/a&gt;s. &lt;a href=\"Deckard%20Cain\"&gt;Deckard Cain&lt;/a&gt; used Orous's writings when compiling his &lt;a href=\"Book%20of%20Cain%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;own work&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "24836", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24836", "title": "Vision Quest", "text": "Vision Quest is a\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Witch%20Doctor\"&gt;Witch Doctor&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0passive skill, unlocked at level 40.\nIn-game.\nThe bonus to Mana regeneration is multiplicative to all other similar modifiers. It does not trigger if the spell hits no enemies."}
{"id": "49831", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49831", "title": "Vision of Enmity", "text": "Visions of Enmity are &lt;a href=\"game%20mode\"&gt;special zones&lt;/a&gt; present in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"Season\"&gt;Season&lt;/a&gt;s starting with Season 29. Each Vision is filled with large quantities of &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt;s and their associated loot. One Vision tends to lead to another, forming chains with a &lt;a href=\"Chests%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;reward chest&lt;/a&gt; at the end. They are accessed via Diabolical Fissures (&lt;a href=\"portal\"&gt;portal&lt;/a&gt;s) which appear randomly from killing monsters in the regular game world.\nAccess.\nWhile adventuring in the main game world (but not a &lt;a href=\"Nephalem%20Rift\"&gt;Nephalem Rift&lt;/a&gt;) in &lt;a href=\"Season\"&gt;Season&lt;/a&gt;al mode, killing a monster has a chance of creating a Diabolical Fissure to a Vision of Enmity, which can be entered immediately. Among the monsters inside, there is usually one which opens another Fissure to another Vision when it is killed. This can continue repeatedly, creating a chain of 1 to 15 Visions in a row. Monster power increases slightly with each level, and scales with overall game &lt;a href=\"difficulty\"&gt;difficulty&lt;/a&gt;. In the last Vision, a special &lt;a href=\"Treasure%20Goblin\"&gt;Treasure Goblin&lt;/a&gt; drops a &lt;a href=\"Diabolic%20Hoard\"&gt;Diabolic Hoard&lt;/a&gt; reward chest. It contains a significant amount of loot, scaling with the number of Visions cleared, and including a fairly large number of the crafting materials normally found from &lt;a href=\"bounty\"&gt;bounty&lt;/a&gt; reward caches (an equal amount of all five types). There is no way to tell how long the chain will be until the last one.\nOpening the Hoard starts a 30 second timer to finish looting before the Visions disappear. Any character still inside them when the timer expires will be teleported to &lt;a href=\"town\"&gt;town&lt;/a&gt;, similar to &lt;a href=\"The%20Vault\"&gt;The Vault&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Echoing%20Nightmare\"&gt;Echoing Nightmare&lt;/a&gt;. Before the Vision closes, players may return to where they had been in the normal game world by working backwards through all the vision levels, although this is unfeasible in longer Vision chains. If they do not, they must travel back to where they were from town.\nDiabolical Fissures can occur quite frequently. For example, while completing the &lt;a href=\"bounties\"&gt;bounties&lt;/a&gt; of an &lt;a href=\"Act\"&gt;Act&lt;/a&gt;, assuming a reasonable number of monsters are killed along the way, it is more likely than not that one or even several will open. The Fissures appear on the &lt;a href=\"map\"&gt;map&lt;/a&gt;, with an arrow pointing to them if far away. The Act map does not show them, however, so players must remember for themselves where to find it if they do not enter immediately. Only one Vision sequence can be open at a time in a game, so if a player chooses to continue adventuring in the normal game world without looting the Hoard from an open Vision, no other portals will appear.\nLevels and maps.\nThere are 15 maps possible for any Vision. They are mostly recreations of small, recognizable zones or areas from the \"Diablo III\" &lt;a href=\"Campaign%20Mode\"&gt;campaign&lt;/a&gt;, but with a different name, and eerie blue glowing cracks in the terrain. They range from as small as &lt;a href=\"The%20Ram\"&gt;The Ram&lt;/a&gt; to as large as &lt;a href=\"Old%20Tristram\"&gt;Old Tristram&lt;/a&gt;. The Visions in a sequence never repeat maps, so the longest possible sequence will have each of the 15 maps one time. The maps can occur in any order.\nEach map has a set location the hero enters from, either a red portal or one of the area's normal exits. The blue portal to the next Vision depends on where the monster happens to spawn it. Other exits normally present in the real world are all locked or blocked.\nEach Vision is populated with one of four categories of monsters:\nThe exact number of monsters is also based on which map they appear in, although Rift Guardians always come in threes. In addition, regardless of the rest of the monsters, there is always either one normal monster which creates the next Diabolical Fissure, or one Treasure Goblin which drops the Diabolic Hoard that ends the Vision sequence.\nList of maps.\nEach map has a special name related to the role or flavor the area plays in the regular world or campaign.\nMonsters.\nThe exact type of monsters present in a Vision varies widely, but any one level tends to have monsters that appear near each other in the normal game world. It is not correlated to which Vision map is present on the level.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Treasure%20Goblin\"&gt;Treasure Goblin&lt;/a&gt; in the final Vision in a sequence is special - it will \"never\" escape, so the player can easily focus on the other monsters before killing it, even leaving and re-entering the zone if desired. It will still try to run away within the current level.\nVisions full of &lt;a href=\"Champion%20monsters\"&gt;Champion&lt;/a&gt; packs can be deadly. They are very densely grouped on most maps, so many different packs may start out right next to the player, and even walking a short distance can unavoidably engage several packs at once. Players will therefore face multiple attacks and instances of &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Skill\"&gt;Monster Skill&lt;/a&gt;s like Thunderstorm and Wallers simultaneously, beyond anything encountered in the normal world.\nThe Treasure Goblin levels will have a mix of varieties, excluding &lt;a href=\"Rainbow%20Goblin\"&gt;Rainbow Goblin&lt;/a&gt;s. They will try to escape through portals as usual, but still must be engaged first (by attacking or moving near them), so depending on the level it is possible to deal with them in groups. They are quite densely populated just like the other levels, so players will certainly have to engage multiple at once, but the rewards are impressive."}
