{"id": "16285", "revid": "4865766", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=16285", "title": "Vita", "text": "Vita is a &lt;a href=\"suffix\"&gt;suffix&lt;/a&gt; that can appear on &lt;a href=\"Charms\"&gt;Charms&lt;/a&gt;. It provides a moderate bonus to &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt;.\nIt can start spawning on items at &lt;a href=\"Item%20Level\"&gt;Item Level&lt;/a&gt; 47, but will not be able to spawn on all items with full effect until level 91. Before this item level, +40 to Life is the highest possible roll.\nVita is the most sought after suffix for Grand Charms that have a +1 to class skills prefix (such as &lt;a href=\"Lion%20Branded\"&gt;Lion Branded&lt;/a&gt;). Due to the very steep requirement of item level 91 needed for a Grand Charm to spawn +41 or higher to Life, only two monsters are able to drop such Grand Charm - Hell &lt;a href=\"Nihlathak\"&gt;Nihlathak&lt;/a&gt; and Hell &lt;a href=\"Baal\"&gt;Baal&lt;/a&gt;. This makes \"41+ Life skiller\" Grand charms extremely rare and very expensive.\nThe common (yet still expensive) strategy of obtaining such Charm is getting a Grand Charm drop from Hell Baal, then using a &lt;a href=\"Horadric%20Cube\"&gt;Horadric Cube&lt;/a&gt; recipe of 3 Perfect &lt;a href=\"Gems%23Diablo_II\"&gt;Gems&lt;/a&gt; + Magic Item for an affix reroll on the Charm, until desired affixes are rolled."}
{"id": "43058", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=43058", "title": "Vitaath", "text": ""}
{"id": "42994", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42994", "title": "Vitaath the Shivering Death", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt; and a member of the &lt;a href=\"Wrathborne\"&gt;Wrathborne&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe laconic demon Vitaath stalks her prey cloaked in frozen wind, and gives chase on icy zephyrs. She relishes nothing so much as the moment her targets find themselves &lt;a href=\"freeze\"&gt;unable to move&lt;/a&gt;. The Shivering Death became a favorite servant of &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt; on the &lt;a href=\"Battlefields%20%20of%20Eternity\"&gt;Battlefields of Eternity&lt;/a&gt;. where her twisted wings and blade were mistaken for those of a fallen &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter &lt;a href=\"Lassal\"&gt;Lassal&lt;/a&gt; was killed, &lt;a href=\"Rayek\"&gt;Rayek&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"the%20Shard-seeker\"&gt;the Shard-seeker&lt;/a&gt; were able to scry Vitaath. She commented that he was always self impressed, but she suffered no distractions. Using the &lt;a href=\"Einfrinn%20Tree\"&gt;Einfrinn Tree&lt;/a&gt;, the Shard-seeker entered her lair in &lt;a href=\"the%20Frigid%20Void\"&gt;the Frigid Void&lt;/a&gt; and defeated her. \nEve of Unmaking.\nC. &lt;a href=\"timeline%231273\"&gt;1273&lt;/a&gt;, Vitaath had resurrected in Hell. At the latter part of the year she\u2014along with &lt;a href=\"Gorgothra\"&gt;Gorgothra&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Beledwe\"&gt;Twin&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Gishtur\"&gt;Terrors&lt;/a&gt;, led a &lt;a href=\"vanguard\"&gt;vanguard&lt;/a&gt; force to the &lt;a href=\"Ashen%20Ravine\"&gt;Ashen Ravine&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\n is a &lt;a href=\"Helliquary\"&gt;Helliquary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". She was introduced in 2. Vitaath is first encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal%20quests\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt; \"&lt;a href=\"Frozen%20in%20Fear\"&gt;Frozen in Fear&lt;/a&gt;\". She is fought in &lt;a href=\"the%20Frigid%20Void\"&gt;the Frigid Void&lt;/a&gt;. She can be challenged on Normal difficulty.\nCombat.\nVitaath's attacks has the following attacks\nAt her last health bar, her attacks change slightly and become more potent."}
{"id": "3141", "revid": "4889310", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3141", "title": "Vitality", "text": "Vitality is a &lt;a href=\"Character%20Attribute\"&gt;Character Attribute&lt;/a&gt; seen throughout the \"Diablo\" universe.\nDiablo/Hellfire.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20%28Game%29\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\", together with the &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; of choice, Vitality indirectly determines the &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; of a hero.\nWhile Vitality can be increased through magical items, it is still under the responsibilities of the &lt;a href=\"Classes\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; to determine Life gains per point.\nFrom top to bottom:\nIt should be taken into consideration that if one wishes to make a Barbarian, his Vitality will also help determine the damage he deals when he does not make use of a shield. This opens the possibility of a Two-handed weapon hero at close range.\nDiablo II/Lord of Destruction.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\", Vitality again determines how much Life a character has, but now also determines the quantity of &lt;a href=\"Stamina\"&gt;Stamina&lt;/a&gt; that a character has.\nVitality can be increased by magical items, but even so, it is still the character's class that determines how much Life is given to the character. The Stamina regeneration rate also increases with more points.\nThe bonus to Life per point in Vitality by class is:\nAll classes receive +1 Stamina per Vitality with the exception of the &lt;a href=\"Assassin\"&gt;Assassin&lt;/a&gt; who gets +1.25 instead.\nPlayers who plan on using items that give bonuses to their Vitality might want to be warned that the Life obtained from those bonuses will \"not\" be affected by items/skills that give +% Life. For example, a Werebear Druid normally has +190% Life from a maxed out Lycanthropy. This would normally give him slightly less than 6 Life per point into Vitality. However, if the same Druid were to apply anything with +Vitality, like the unique charm &lt;a href=\"Annihilus\"&gt;Annihilus&lt;/a&gt;, the bonus Life he'd get from the enchantments will only be 2 per point.\nDiablo III.\nVitality returns in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", once again as the stat that determines a character's Life. The effects are small at only 10 Life per point initially, but the gains begin to increase in value depending on the following level ranges:\nIt should be noted that Classic players can only go up to the level cap of 60. Thus, they must upgrade to the expansion if they wish more gains out of their Vitality, or gather equipment that gives a % bonus to total Life.\nOne may increase Vitality through finding equipment that offers affixes that specifically increase that stat. &lt;a href=\"Amethyst\"&gt;Amethyst&lt;/a&gt; gems will also offer Vitality if they are placed in a socket that is not a weapon or helm socket; up to +280 per gem. The &lt;a href=\"Paragon\"&gt;Paragon&lt;/a&gt; system also allows all players to place their Core points into Vitality, with no cap other than what is allowed by their Paragon level.\nUpon leveling up in the normal system, all players gain +2 Vitality, no matter their specializations."}
{"id": "43326", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=43326", "title": "Vitalya", "text": "Biography.\nVitalya was a master at the Sanctified Earth Monastery. Two of his students were &lt;a href=\"Oza\"&gt;Oza&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dravec\"&gt;Dravec&lt;/a&gt;. Shortly after the &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231265\"&gt;fall of Arreat&lt;/a&gt;, he separated a spar between his students when Dravec called upon the &lt;a href=\"Skarn\"&gt;God of Retribution&lt;/a&gt; to attack Oza. He then chastised Dravec. \nShortly before 1270, Dravec assaulted him to find where the Worldstone shard was hidden. Unfortunately for him, Dravec was empowered by Skarn and was easily able to overpower then kill him when he refused to divulge the location of the shard.\nIn game.\nVitalya appears in the side quest \"&lt;a href=\"Mastery%20and%20Nothingness\"&gt;Mastery and Nothingness&lt;/a&gt;\" in &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;. He is also mentioned in some of the lore for the gears of the &lt;a href=\"Monk%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Class%23Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "51625", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51625", "title": "Vithu", "text": "Vithu was an artist.\nBiography.\nWhen Vithu stood even a few feet off the ground, he heard his own voice urging him to jump. Once he could no longer sleep, he painted the tenebrous &lt;a href=\"Void\"&gt;Void&lt;/a&gt; he saw in his dreams. Vithu's paintings were adored throughout the provinces, and many called him a seer. Patrons chased the sublimity of his feelings. In one year, a dozen leaping &lt;a href=\"death\"&gt;death&lt;/a&gt;s from the heights were recorded in &lt;a href=\"Fengge\"&gt;Fengge&lt;/a&gt;. Vithu was consumed by guilt and left Fengge, vowing to paint no more. A year later he was visited by a young girl asking for his work, with a penknife held unsteadily in her hand. Vithu opened his door with downcast eyes, certain that she had come for revenge. He was shocked when she begged to be his apprentice.\nThe girl, &lt;a href=\"Miray\"&gt;Miray&lt;/a&gt;, confessed that she imagined the Void years ago, and drew it for her parents. If Vithu was guilty of their deaths, she was as well. But she preferred to blame the Void. Vithu accepted Miray's apprenticeship, and they painted the Void in new colors, undeniable but robbed of all its power. Eventually, Vithu was surpassed by his student in talent, which aroused fury in him towards her. He painted the void in deep colors on her ceiling which immediately began to darken. By the time she returned that night he was gone, and perfectly oval holes cut through the roof and floor of her home.\nIn-game.\nVithu is mentioned in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\" in the text flavor of \"&lt;a href=\"Vithu%27s%20Urges\"&gt;Vithu's Urges&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"item%20set\"&gt;item set&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "51406", "revid": "2011810", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51406", "title": "Vithu's Urges", "text": " is an &lt;a href=\"item%20set\"&gt;item set&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\"."}
{"id": "17010", "revid": "99965", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=17010", "title": "Vitriolic Missile", "text": "Vitriolic Missile or Poison Ball is a poisonous projectile usually shot from a wall or other obstacle by the result of triggering &lt;a href=\"Traps\"&gt;a trap&lt;/a&gt;. While traveling it leaves a trail of &lt;a href=\"poison%20cloud\"&gt;poison cloud&lt;/a&gt; behind it. This projectile is similar to a spike ball in being moderately slow moving so it is easy to dodge. The missile itself does only mild physical damage but poison clouds are lethal in large doses at least for the hero's companions.\nVitriolic Missiles are usually seen along with spike balls in the depths of the Kehjistan Jungle where the aboriginal people have booby trapped their sacred statues and monoliths."}
{"id": "44490", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44490", "title": "Viv Mesztros", "text": "Viv Mesztros The Lively was a member of the &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20Terror\"&gt;Cult of Terror&lt;/a&gt; that \nattacked &lt;a href=\"Stormpoint%20Keep\"&gt;Stormpoint Keep&lt;/a&gt;.\nBiography.\nViv Mesztros was a member and one of the leaders of &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20Terror\"&gt;Cult of Terror&lt;/a&gt;. In &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231272\"&gt;1272&lt;/a&gt; she, along with &lt;a href=\"Akinees\"&gt;Akinees&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Bride%20of%20Hell\"&gt;Bride of Hell&lt;/a&gt;, attacked &lt;a href=\"Stormpoint%20Keep\"&gt;Stormpoint Keep&lt;/a&gt; in order to retrieve &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone's&lt;/a&gt; shard. Viv killed several defenders, but was slain by &lt;a href=\"the%20Shard-seeker\"&gt;the Shard-seeker&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nViv Mesztros is a &lt;a href=\"Bloodsworn%20Priestess\"&gt;Bloodsworn Priestess&lt;/a&gt;, and a &lt;a href=\"boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". She is encountered in &lt;a href=\"Unexpected%20Reinforcement\"&gt;Unexpected Reinforcement&lt;/a&gt;, at &lt;a href=\"Stormpoint%20Keep\"&gt;Stormpoint Keep&lt;/a&gt;.\nShe has the standard abilities of a Bloodsworn Priestess, albeit flame themed. Apart from that, she has the waller and jailer &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Traits%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;traits&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "1893", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1893", "title": "Viz-Jaq'taar", "text": "The Viz-Jaq'taar, otherwise known as the \"Order of the Mage Slayers\" or simply \"&lt;a href=\"Assassin\"&gt;Assassin&lt;/a&gt;s,\" are a secretive order whose task is to weed out &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;ic corruption from the &lt;a href=\"Mage%20Clans\"&gt;Mage Clans&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe Order's code is based on passages from &lt;a href=\"Lam%20Esen%27s%20Tome%20%28Item%29\"&gt;Lam Esen's Tome&lt;/a&gt;. The Order remains veiled in secrecy, and few people, even among the Mage Clans, know of its existence. However, the mere rumor of their existence has been enough to prevent many mages from falling into temptation.\nAbilities.\nKnowing that the Order might be itself corrupted if exposed to magic, the Vizjerei deemed that the Assassins would have to possess the purest, most focused minds, that they should draw their power from within, not without. As such, the Order does not employ magic directly. Rather, Assassins use ingenious devices and enchanted items to battle those possessing great magical powers. To further their campaign against demonic corruption, they hone the natural martial abilities of their bodies, both physical and mental/psychic. They train extensively in the use of a specialised type of weapon\u2014special blades that are attached to their wrists, which are used in conjunction with their style of martial arts. Additionally, Assassins are masters of infiltration, using a variety of shadow disciplines.\nThe martial arts techniques used by Assassins fall into two groups. The first type are &lt;a href=\"Charge-up%20Skill\"&gt;charge-up moves&lt;/a&gt;, attacks that add a \"charge\" for each successful attack done within a short period of time. The second type is the &lt;a href=\"Finishing%20Moves\"&gt;finishing move&lt;/a&gt;, which follows charge-up strikes, adding a charge of its own.\nHistory.\nThe Order has its origins in the &lt;a href=\"Mage%20Clan%20Wars\"&gt;Mage Clan Wars&lt;/a&gt;. In the aftermath of the conflict, the &lt;a href=\"Vizjerei\"&gt;Vizjerei&lt;/a&gt; foreswore the use of demonic &lt;a href=\"magic\"&gt;magic&lt;/a&gt;. To this end, the Viz-jaq'taar were created, a secret order whose sole goal was to police the Mage Clans.\nAt some point after the &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Exile\"&gt;Dark Exile&lt;/a&gt;, the Viz-Jaq'taar fought a war against the &lt;a href=\"Horadrim\"&gt;Horadrim&lt;/a&gt;.\nDuring the return of the &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evil\"&gt;Prime Evil&lt;/a&gt;s, the Order's actions became more public. They dispatched one of their own to investigate, the assassin in question allying with a &lt;a href=\"Classes%23Diablo%20II\"&gt;group of heroes&lt;/a&gt; who prevented the Prime Evils' schemes from coming into fruition."}
