{"id": "51514", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51514", "title": "Tempering", "text": "Tempering is a crafting system in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\", introduced in .\nTo carry out Tempering, the player must find &lt;a href=\"Tempering%20Manual\"&gt;Tempering Manual&lt;/a&gt;s, which &lt;a href=\"blacksmith\"&gt;blacksmith&lt;/a&gt;s can use to shape the qualities of &lt;a href=\"items\"&gt;items&lt;/a&gt;. Tempering allows players to add potent affixes to items. Most items can only have a single affix, while &lt;a href=\"Ancestral%20Items\"&gt;Ancestral Items&lt;/a&gt; can have two Tempered affixes from different categories.\nTempering durability indicates how many times an item can be tempered. "}
{"id": "51515", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51515", "title": "Tempering Manual", "text": "Tempering Manuals (a.k.a. Crafting Manuals) are a type of &lt;a href=\"item\"&gt;item&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\", introduced in .\nTempering Manuals can be found throughout the game. Once learned, they can be used as many times as desired. Each Crafting Manual contains a small number of affixes, and typically correspond to six different categories: Weapons, Offensive, Defensive, Mobility, Utility and Resource. A player can head to a &lt;a href=\"blacksmith\"&gt;blacksmith&lt;/a&gt; to use the manual through the game's &lt;a href=\"tempering\"&gt;tempering&lt;/a&gt; system.\nManuals learnt on the &lt;a href=\"Seasonal%20Realm\"&gt;Seasonal Realm&lt;/a&gt; last until the end of the , while manuals learned on the &lt;a href=\"Eternal%20Realm\"&gt;Eternal Realm&lt;/a&gt; are known permanently."}
{"id": "51468", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51468", "title": "Tempest", "text": "The Tempest is a &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; for \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". It became playable as part of a free &lt;a href=\"Unending%20Storm\"&gt;update&lt;/a&gt; in May, 2024.\nLore.\nTempests are warrior-priests based in the &lt;a href=\"Cold%20Isles\"&gt;Cold Isles&lt;/a&gt;. Chosen from among the pure of heart, Tempests are raised to protect their people. \nAbilities.\nTempests wear waterproof, lightweight armor. They train in fighting upon the waves, and excel in blade-dancing, wavewalking, and seafaring. They harness movement and elemental powers as they unleash twin &lt;a href=\"edge\"&gt;edge&lt;/a&gt;s; wind and water blades of immense power that harness the elements of air and water. Tempests can move and morph like water to both maneuver around the battlefield and damage enemies. They can also conjure &lt;a href=\"Zephyr\"&gt;Zephyr&lt;/a&gt;s;temporary shades that mirror the Tempest's movements to distract and taunt enemies, leaving their foes open for the kill. However, unlike the &lt;a href=\"druids\"&gt;druids&lt;/a&gt;, tempests do not wield their power over the northern elements in harmony with nature. They command wind and wave in the tongues of forgotten empresses, and twist their power in unnatural ways.\nTraining.\nProspective tempests (called Bladedancers) begin training from a young age. They are at first given reeds and sticks to master channeling of the northern elements and the Samilian martial style. As they master each element (when they are able to channel it without splitting or damaging their weapons) they are given a wind edge or wave edge, signifying the element mastered. \nThe purest and bravest of the Tempests are sent on dangerous voyages to breathe in the mists of &lt;a href=\"the%20Spiral\"&gt;the Spiral&lt;/a&gt;. To hear the whispering voices of an earlier age, and grow in knowledge and power to command sea and sky as Empress &lt;a href=\"Mehrwen\"&gt;Mehrwen&lt;/a&gt; did. The Tempests who are purest of heart and will drink the mists in daily, ultimately trading their material thoughts and bodies for greater power over wave and wind. Symptoms preclude this stage, which are visible in a Tempest's reflection.\nHistory.\nThe history of Tempests goes back thousands of years, and their attire has remained the same throughout their history. Their origins stem back to &lt;a href=\"Pelghain\"&gt;Pelghain&lt;/a&gt;\u2014after the empire's collapse, the empire's once proud people turned to the Tempests for protection. They sailed as far south as the &lt;a href=\"Northern%20Steppes\"&gt;Northern Steppes&lt;/a&gt; to hunt the beasts that ravaged their shores. However, storms continued to batter the Cold Isles for centuries, and more Tempests were needed to curb them each year. With each beast the Tempests slew, two more lurked below. However, the rulers of the Isles refused to abandon their homeland.\nOver time, a number of Tempests have strayed from their home. Indeed, some Tempests voyage widely, and have beheld a world just as embatted as their homeland. This has led some Tempests to reject their society and refuse to lose their humanity to the mists. Those who abandon the Cold Isles are made pariahs, in order to deter others from following their example, but for these Tempests, their calling is to use their talents to protect the lives of mainlanders at all costs. They claim their perspective is greater than that of the mist-addled &lt;a href=\"Unmoored\"&gt;Unmoored&lt;/a&gt;, and lament their strongest wasting their lives; delaying the inevitable, never stopping it. Some believe their home will be doomed forever. \nc. &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231273\"&gt;1273&lt;/a&gt;, a small group of Tempests voyaged to the mainland to confront its evils. They cut down &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;s with blade and water, and sought to preserve any lives they could. But when they spoke, it was always as exiles\u2014with the chill of the wind and the voices of centuries gone. If their home was doomed despite all their people had sacrificed, what would it cost them to save Sanctuary?\nGameplay.\nTempests are based around dual-wielding blades. Their abilities are themed around water and wind. This allows them to lash enemies with water whips, swirl around to target enemies and trap &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt;s to dash through them for increased damage. They are a &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt;-based class.\nWhen playing as the Tempest, players have access to an exclusive &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt;, \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Relentless%20Tide\"&gt;The Relentless Tide&lt;/a&gt;.\" This depicts the backstory of the Tempest class and takes place 2-3 years before \"Immortal\" begins. However, the quest can be skipped if the player so chooses. The Tempest class also has a trial dungeon which has pre-builds meant to allow players to test out various styles.\nDevelopment.\nDevelopment on the Tempest began after the release of the &lt;a href=\"Blood%20Knight%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;Blood Knight&lt;/a&gt;. Early on, the developers were toying with early ideas for a wind and wave class. Concepts existed for classes such as the Sage and Siren. There was also an illusionist-type character.\nOne of the key ideas that the designers had for the Tempest was to create a narrative surrounding the class from the beginning of development. They used that narrative to drive the design, rather than creating the class first. The idea of the &lt;a href=\"Cold%20Isles\"&gt;Cold Isles&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Pelghain\"&gt;Pelghain&lt;/a&gt; was developed first, which drove the idea for the class to be characterized by the elements of wind and water. The idea for this came from looking at the &lt;a href=\"Frozen%20Sea\"&gt;Frozen Sea&lt;/a&gt; and asking what was up there. As of 2023, there was little material that depicted the area.\nIt was decided that the Tempest was going to be movement-based, and control water and wind. To accentuate the water and wind elements, the developers took inspiration from telltale patterns and art nouveau due to the style's use of curvy lines that further accentuate the theme and their movement overall. It was decided to use a cooler color palette for the Tempest, making it visually distinct from other classes within the game.\nEarlier in production, the Tempest was going to look completely different from its final version. At some point, it was going to look like a sea creature, akin to a half-human, half sea creature. When the theme of the Tempest was discussed, the developers had a chart where they looked at the other classes of the franchise. They saw that they didn't have much of a light-based, light-themed class that is not holy or &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt;ic. The developers wanted something that was life-based to contrast with the Blood Knight. Thus, the visuals were changed to make the Tempest more human. The Tempest's color scheme is primarily white and teal, setting it apart from other classes. The white and teal colors stemmed from the idea of a class with a brighter color palette. Furthermore, the colors sync with the Tempest's fluidity, lightweight gear, and the chaos of storms.\n&lt;a href=\"Nephalem\"&gt;Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; lore inspired the design of the Tempest.\nVisually, one of the key differences that sets the Tempest apart from other is the main weapon that they use, namely swords where the blade can separate from the hilt and turn into a water whip.\nDuring development, it was considered making the Tempest a summons-based class, akin to the &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;. This only went as far as the Zephyr, and it was designed to make the Zephyr feel like a mimic of the Tempest as opposed to a summoned creature.\nThe Tempest was first hinted at in March, 2024, where it was announced that a new class would be released for the game, and would not be a pre-existing class. The class was formally revealed in May of the same year."}
