{"id": "32270", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32270", "title": "Templar Inquisition", "text": "Templar Inquisition is an Exploration &lt;a href=\"bounty\"&gt;bounty&lt;/a&gt; in of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It can only happen in &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt;, and takes place in &lt;a href=\"the%20Weeping%20Hollow\"&gt;the Weeping Hollow&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe goal is to rescue three Templar \"recruits\" in three random points across the valley. Each will be chained to a stake and surrounded by two dozen Templar Enforcers and Arbalests. Each group is led by a Maester, either &lt;a href=\"Maester%20Gnaeus\"&gt;Maester Gnaeus&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Maester%20Julius\"&gt;Maester Julius&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Maester%20Licinius\"&gt;Maester Licinius&lt;/a&gt;.\nUntying each recruit can only be performed once all guards are dead. They exit through town portals immediately upon release. Rescuing all three concludes the event.\nDue to the wide distribution of recruits throughout the zone, it can sometimes be useful to use the &lt;a href=\"waypoint\"&gt;waypoint&lt;/a&gt; to the &lt;a href=\"Cemetery%20of%20the%20Forsaken\"&gt;Cemetery of the Forsaken&lt;/a&gt; to reach a recruit from the north."}
{"id": "32271", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32271", "title": "Templar Inquisition (Event)", "text": ""}
{"id": "19014", "revid": "46404728", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19014", "title": "Templar Order", "text": "The Templar Order was a group of holy warriors dedicated to the &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt;, renowned for their ferocity, tenacity, and prowess in battle.\nLore.\nThe Templar were founded as holy warriors, fighting for justice and eschewing the dangers that lead to cultism and demonic possession by espousing self-denial. They did not merely pay lip service to protecting &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;\u2014they were battle-trained and experienced to a man. The chalices, vials, and sacred texts of the Templar Order often inspire a deep reverence in those who view or hold them.\nThere is evidence that once, the Templar Order was a more benign force than what they ended up becoming. Regardless, by the &lt;a href=\"End%20of%20Days\"&gt;End of Days&lt;/a&gt;, the Templar Order abducted innocent citizens and subjected them to horrific torture, purging their memories and molding them into zealous adherents. This occurred within \"rue chambers\"\u2014rooms within Templar strongholds where the penitents were \"reeducated\" through scourges and whips, to renounce their past \"sins\" and give themselves over to the Zakarum faith. The Templars &lt;a href=\"Kormac\"&gt;Kormac&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Jondar\"&gt;Jondar&lt;/a&gt; are two such examples of this practice being carried out.\nIn terms of organization, the Order was led by a &lt;a href=\"Grand%20Maester\"&gt;Grand Maester&lt;/a&gt;. Its subordinate membership consisted of &lt;a href=\"Inquisitor\"&gt;Inquisitor&lt;/a&gt;s and Templar themselves. The Order's membership was entirely male. It is implied that the Templar had vows against romance, marriage, intercourse, etc.\nHistory.\nThe Order remained an enigma to many on the outside, and there were rumors regarding their exact founding and purpose. Though the Templars professed a dedication to the Light and seek to rid &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;ic corruption, they were not officially sanctioned by the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum\"&gt;Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; church. Rather, they rose from the ashes of the &lt;a href=\"Hand%20of%20Zakarum\"&gt;Hand of Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; after it fell to corruption by &lt;a href=\"Mephisto\"&gt;Mephisto&lt;/a&gt;, and they viewed themselves as the new, pure continuation of that faith. In the mind of &lt;a href=\"Diadra\"&gt;Diadra&lt;/a&gt;, the Templars \"represented all that &lt;a href=\"Akarat\"&gt;Akarat&lt;/a&gt; intended\" before they were led astray by the &lt;a href=\"Grand%20Maester\"&gt;Grand Maester&lt;/a&gt;.\"\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"End%20of%20Days\"&gt;End of Days&lt;/a&gt;, the Templar searched for their holy scrolls, stolen by &lt;a href=\"Archbishop%20Lazarus\"&gt;Archbishop Lazarus&lt;/a&gt;. It was found that the Order was involved in the creation of &lt;a href=\"magic\"&gt;magic&lt;/a&gt;al weapons, &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt;ic in nature, but designed for &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; hands.\nStorm of Light.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231285\"&gt;1285&lt;/a&gt;, a branch of the Templar under the command of Lord &lt;a href=\"Norlun\"&gt;Norlun&lt;/a&gt; took control of the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum%20Cathedral\"&gt;Zakarum Cathedral&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Westmarch%20%28City%29\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt;, renaming it the \"Church of the Holy Order.\" They quickly established a sense of authority over the capital's citizens, even if they possessed no official standing. Tensions quickly developed between the Templar and the &lt;a href=\"Knights%20of%20Westmarch\"&gt;Knights of Westmarch&lt;/a&gt;. While some knights defected to the Templar, most remained true to their own order. The Zakarum Cathedral had once been the Knights' base of operations, and the slight of the Templar taking it as their own had not gone unnoticed.\nThe Knights came to believe that the Templar were planning a rebellion against King &lt;a href=\"Justinian%20IV\"&gt;Justinian IV&lt;/a&gt;. Whatever the truth of the matter, the Knights moved against the Templar, but their plans were leaked by an informant. As such, the Templar were ready for them. Combat began in the streets, while Templar archers manned the cathedral. However, the Templar found themselves under attack by the &lt;a href=\"Horadrim\"&gt;Horadrim&lt;/a&gt; as well, who attacked them from the rear.\nThe Knights fought their way into the cathedral, but the Templar refused to surrender, and made their stand in the cathedral's underground chambers. Most of them refused to surrender, and some even fought with their bare hands. Eventually, Norlu threw down his weapon and ordered the remaining Templar to yield. The Knights disarmed the remaining Templar, and Norlun was hauled away to meet the hangman's noose.\nReaper of Souls.\nLater in the year, when the Nephalem came to &lt;a href=\"Westmarch\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt; to stop the onslaught of &lt;a href=\"Malthael\"&gt;Malthael&lt;/a&gt; and his &lt;a href=\"Reapers\"&gt;Reapers&lt;/a&gt;, Kormac learned that the Templar Order was meeting in the Vault of the Order, their great fortress in the city, and resolved to find out how deeply their corruption ran. When the Nephalem and Kormac entered the Vault, Kormac was hailed as one of the greatest Templars the order had ever seen for his role in destroying &lt;a href=\"Belial\"&gt;Belial&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Azmodan\"&gt;Azmodan&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href=\"The%20Grand%20Maester%27s%20Proclamation\"&gt;newest proclamation by the Grand Maester&lt;/a&gt; was given to them, which laid bare the Grand Maester's intent to turn every citizen of Westmarch, and beyond, into Templars in preparation for a \"day of reckoning\", an announcement that Kormac called \"damning\", indisputable proof that the corruption of the order went straight to the top. Kormac and the Nephalem came across the Templar Inquisitors preparing to torture a new Templar initiate, which Kormac swiftly put a stop to by demanding to know how they could do this to a fellow Templar. Kormac and the Nephalem were taken into the presence of the Grand Maester, who praised Kormac for his heroics before announcing his intention to name him as his successor as Grand Maester. Kormac refused, calling the Grand Maester and his Inquisitors out for lying to and betraying every Templar, beginning with the torture of their initiation.\nThe Grand Maester ordered the Inquisitors to kill Kormac and the Nephalem, but the two quickly proved too much for their combined forces to stop, and the Grand Maester fled. Kormac and the Nephalem pursued him, killing every Inquisitor who attempted to stop them. The two finally cornered the Grand Maester and his most loyal bodyguard in the courtyard of the Vault, and in a furious battle, the Grand Maester and his Inquisitors were defeated and slain, bringing an end to the Templar Order and its corruption as it stood. As Kormac and the Nephalem prepared to return to the Survivors' Enclave, Kormac vowed to track down every Templar still indoctrinated by the Order and show them the error of their ways, by force if need be."}
{"id": "19925", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19925", "title": "Templar Relic", "text": "Templar Relics are charm-like special items, specific to the \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"Followers\"&gt;follower&lt;/a&gt; Templar class. These relics boost &lt;a href=\"Kormac\"&gt;Kormac&lt;/a&gt; the Templar's abilities and attributes. The Templar Relic cannot be equipped to a player or other follower classes. These relics are the Order's sacred items: ritual chalices, shards of holy blades, sanctified texts and holy water vials.\nTemplar Relics can roll up to 6 affixes that can normally be rolled on an amulet (except sockets, &lt;a href=\"Critical%20Hit\"&gt;critical hit&lt;/a&gt; chance, &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; %, class-specific affixes or player-only characteristics bonuses). As of patch 2.0,\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Magic%20Find\"&gt;Magic Find&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0cannot roll on the follower items. There are no special affixes exclusive to Templar, except for legendary guaranteed effects (see below).\nRare quality relics can be crafted by the\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Haedrig%20Eamon\"&gt;Blacksmith&lt;/a&gt;.\nThere are three Legendary relics Kormac can use, all of them drop at level 61 or later:"}
